results.notes:
At first glance we thought this was a species of Caloboletus. But, the flesh in the cap tasted mild. I nibbled it twice.
The sectioned fruit body stained blue inside the cap within a couple minutes. The scratched pore surface darkened slightly. By the following day the stained areas had turned reddish-brown. This pattern of staining suggests Lanmaoa. But the fruit body does not look like any species of Lanmaoa I am aware of.
Except for the blue-to-brown staining across most of the cap context, this reminds me of Boletus huronensis.
Collected at the Bill Russell Foray.
Submitted for sequencing.

results.notes:
Paxillus panuoides (yellow variant) description
Found 8/24/23, growing on deadwood along the Trevlac Nature Reserve trail. A few of them, shelving laterally on the log; some overlapping.
Caps: Smaller ones mostly yellow, with orange-brown toward the attachment. Larger ones yellow only near the edges, then dark orange-brown. Shape: fan-shaped, some with wavy lobes. Margins incurled especially in smaller caps. Dry, fuzzy texture. Soft but firm. Flesh yellow, 5 mm thick.
KOH on cap: black.
No stalk. Flesh at attachment point is orange.
Gills: dark brownish orange; crowded, crimped and wavy throughout, forking repeatedly.
Spore print: yellow.
Spores: Oblong / short cylindric, smooth walled. 3.2-5.2 × 2-2.3 microns. Staining reaction with Melzer’s: none.
Comments: This appears to be a yellower variant of Paxillus panuoides (aka tapinella panuoides). Both the cap and flesh are yellow (although the central part of the cap is orange/brown). The spores are also different from those of P. panuoides. However, the shape, lack of stem, crimped/wavy gills and yellow spore print are all suggestive of this species.

results.notes:
Mushrooms keep growing in green waste compost from local e-waste site and leaf mold added to local garden as mulch. They look like little (or big) pancakes, usually 1 – 6 inches across, tops grow close to the ground but there are stems under, typically tall or medium height. Underside seems to have teeth or pores (I am a novice!) As they age they curl up at edges and crack on top, revealing more of the textured underside. They appear often in clumps. Soil is kept fairly moist (watered every other day or so) and only partial sun, mostly shade from overhead trees. Deep or tawny yellow color to underside and stem. Tops are truly light brown pancakes color and pattern. At least 1/4 – 1/2 inch thick tops, if not thicker. Something seems to take a bite of them here or there, (squirrel or possum?) But usually they are left alone or dug up and left.
They have a strong salty urine smell or very stinky sock smell when they age, possibly all the time.
Thank you, I’d appreciate any help with ID!

results.notes:
Are these stone mushrooms? Or puffballs? Rock mushroom? They are growing in green waste compost from local e-waste site and leaf mold added to local garden as mulch. Soil is kept fairly moist (watered every other day or so) and only partial sun, mostly shade from overhead trees or cover. Sometimes they grow in surrounding areas that have little to no irrigation.

results.notes:
Hericium corraloides description
Found 8/27/23 growing on a fallen hardwood tree, in the woods near Lake Lemon, Brown County, IN. A single fruiting body.
Fruiting body pure white, growing from a single stem with many branches dividing repeatedly. The stem and branches are covered in fine white spines which are regularly spaced and dense; there are tufts of spines at the ends of some branches. The spines range in size from 3 mm tall on the stem, to 5 mm on the branches and up to 1 cm tall on the ends of branches; 1 mm wide or less. Branches are 0.5 – 1 cm thick. Overall size is 9 cm tall, 15 cm wide. Odor sweet.
KOH on a branch turned pale yellow.
Spore print white. Spores spheroid or sub-spheroid, smooth to minutely roughened (roughening just barely visible at 1000x). 3.6-4.5 × 3.6-4.0 microns.
Staining reaction with Melzer’s: amyloid.
